## What This Is

A **dOSPO** (Decentralized Open Source Program Office) is a community-mandated coordination layer that:

- **Separates policy authority from operational execution** — community governance sets direction; a bounded operator executes it
- **Provides coordination without consolidation** — no project ownership, no roadmap control, no IP accumulation
- **Decays unless renewed** — mandates expire on a 2–4 year charter cycle; continuation requires active community re-authorization
- **Fills the gap** that DAOs, foundations, and corporate OSPOs each leave open: bounded, accountable execution in distributed authority environments

This repository provides a **reference architecture** — a set of templates, governance documents, and operational specs — that any sufficiently mature Web3 ecosystem can fork and adapt.

> ⚠️ A dOSPO is **not** appropriate for small or experimental ecosystems. It is designed for ecosystems with high dependency depth, distributed authority across multiple independent entities, and failures that impose ecosystem-wide cost. See [When Not To Use This](#when-to-use-this).

