## The Three Policy Domains

Policy authority is distributed across three community-mandated bodies. The operator executes within the frameworks these bodies define — it does not define them.

### 🟦 Open Source Domain
> *"What does it mean for a project to be well-maintained in this ecosystem?"*

Governed by a **Stewardship Committee** or **Open Source Council**. Sets:
- Project lifecycle criteria (exploration → growth → maturity → sunset)
- Funding eligibility standards
- Transparency and reporting requirements
- Contribution guidelines and repository standards
- Licensing policy for the broader open source portfolio (including dApps)

→ [`governance/open-source-domain.md`](governance/open-source-domain.md)

---

### 🟩 Technical Domain
> *"How do projects that share infrastructure make decisions together?"*

Governed by a **Technical Steering Group** or **Technical Council**. Sets:
- Interoperability requirements across projects
- Cross-project dependency conflict resolution
- Technical gating for lifecycle transitions
- Quality and integration standards for funded work
- Architectural alignment for shared infrastructure changes

→ [`governance/technical-domain.md`](governance/technical-domain.md)

---

### 🟥 Security Domain
> *"Who has the authority to act fast during an incident, and for how long?"*

Governed by a **Security Council** or **Security Advisory Board**. Sets:
- Responsible disclosure policy and embargo timelines
- Severity taxonomy (shared across all ecosystem projects)
- Pre-authorized emergency execution authority for the operator
- Conditions under which emergency authority expands — and contracts
- Post-incident review requirements

→ [`governance/security-domain.md`](governance/security-domain.md)

